The family firm Giovanni Agnelli B.V. owns 52.99% of the share capital.
Exor is ranked 19th largest company by revenue according to the 2015 and 2016 Fortune Global 500 lists.[3]
Mergers, shares and acquisitions[edit]
PartnerRe[edit]
In 2015 Exor bought PartnerRe with a bid of $140 per share (total $6.9 billions).[6] Originally it had offered $130 per share and in response Axis Re offered $120.31 per share in paper plus $11.50 in a pre-closing dividend.[7]
The Economist[edit]
On August 12, 2015, the editor announced that Exor will purchase three-fifths of the Economist Group shares currently owned by Pearson PLC.[8] Exor held shares in the Economist Group prior to this purchase.[8] This is considered to be the "most important change to The Economist's shareholding structure in almost 90 years."[8] Pearson PLC which also owns the Financial Times has had a non-controlling 50% stake in the Economist Group since 1928. The Economist Group will buy back the remained two-fifths of Pearson shares.[9][8]
